WEBVTT

00:01.209 --> 00:04.169
[INSTRUMENTAL MUSIC]

00:15.390 --> 00:20.390
Subtitles by explosiveskull

00:23.356 --> 00:24.315
Libby.

00:28.402 --> 00:29.361
Libby.

00:32.198 --> 00:33.115
Libby.

00:37.203 --> 00:38.996
You did amazing work.

00:41.165 --> 00:43.083
I knew I could count on you.

01:06.900 --> 01:09.819
[INSTRUMENTAL MUSIC]

03:08.020 --> 03:10.562
[BELLS TOLLING]

03:10.564 --> 03:13.526
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

03:18.073 --> 03:20.280
[PEOPLE CHANTING]
Peace or terror!

03:20.282 --> 03:22.201
[SIREN BLARING]

03:31.461 --> 03:34.172
[CHANTING CONTINUES]

03:41.680 --> 03:44.599
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

03:58.195 --> 03:59.779
[INDISTINCT RADIO CHATTER]

03:59.781 --> 04:02.742
[INSTRUMENTAL MUSIC]

04:10.000 --> 04:11.668
What a morning.

04:13.002 --> 04:18.880
Students, welcome to
Course number 422, cap 23

04:18.882 --> 04:21.884
Understanding
Contemporary Warfare.

04:21.886 --> 04:24.469
I apologize for the hullabaloo

04:24.471 --> 04:27.098
you may have encountered
entering the building

04:27.100 --> 04:29.933
but it was a one-off,
I can assure you.

04:29.935 --> 04:31.519
As you may or may not be aware

04:31.521 --> 04:35.106
Professor Shimka, who was
scheduled to teach this course

04:35.108 --> 04:37.692
suffered a heart attack
some weeks back.

04:37.694 --> 04:39.819
In his stead, we are honored

04:39.821 --> 04:42.822
to have secured
the services and talents

04:42.824 --> 04:46.034
of one of the most brilliant
and innovative minds

04:46.036 --> 04:50.663
in American foreign policy
today, Elizabeth Lamm.

04:50.665 --> 04:53.957
Elizabeth received her BA
from Princeton

04:53.959 --> 04:57.336
and her Ph.D.
from the University of Chicago.

04:57.338 --> 05:01.257
Fluent in French,
Japanese, Pashtu..

05:01.259 --> 05:03.177
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

05:24.324 --> 05:27.449
Winter break, I'm getting
the left hip replaced.

05:27.451 --> 05:29.577
End of the school year,
the right one.

05:29.579 --> 05:32.079
Already, I've had
both knees worked on.

05:32.081 --> 05:35.123
I have the best orthopedic guy,
if you're ever in need.

05:35.125 --> 05:37.293
- Not yet, anyway.
- Willa?

05:37.295 --> 05:39.503
Oh, how did it go?
How crazy was it?

05:39.505 --> 05:40.630
Were arrests made?

05:40.632 --> 05:42.839
Campus cops handled it
with aplomb

05:42.841 --> 05:44.384
a very pleasant surprise.

05:44.386 --> 05:45.885
Wouldn't you agree, Elizabeth?

05:45.887 --> 05:47.803
Yes, security was excellent.

05:47.805 --> 05:49.639
Gracious, my manners.

05:49.641 --> 05:51.182
Everything's moved so fast

05:51.184 --> 05:53.351
I forget you've only
just arrived.

05:53.353 --> 05:55.105
Elizabeth, this is Dee.

05:56.689 --> 05:57.606
Elizabeth.

06:02.194 --> 06:06.781
Without Dee, the office would come
to a grinding and very messy halt.

06:06.783 --> 06:08.949
Whatever you need,
just let us know.

06:08.951 --> 06:10.868
Thank you. I will.

06:10.870 --> 06:12.536
Martin!

06:12.538 --> 06:14.788
There he is,
my phantom roommate

06:14.790 --> 06:18.125
the international
man of mystery.

06:18.127 --> 06:20.252
- Jordan.
- Where you've been?

06:20.254 --> 06:21.336
Like, I know we've
only known each other

06:21.338 --> 06:22.546
a short time, but I worry.

06:22.548 --> 06:23.714
It's my nature, right?

06:23.716 --> 06:26.591
I'm like my Jewish
grandmother that way.

06:26.593 --> 06:29.055
Just, uh, just shoot me
a text, or something.

06:31.557 --> 06:32.889
"Great seeing you too, Jordan."

06:32.891 --> 06:34.392
Thanks for givin' a shit.

06:34.394 --> 06:36.685
You're right, I could've
fallen in a lake and drowned.

06:36.687 --> 06:38.272
- No one would ever have known.
- Thank you.

06:40.108 --> 06:42.569
Hey, any time, roomie.

06:47.906 --> 06:50.159
And this is you.

06:55.331 --> 06:59.252
I'm afraid it's rather Spartan
in terms of creature comforts.

07:02.379 --> 07:04.964
It's perfect, actually.

07:04.966 --> 07:08.050
Well, it may not
be Foggy Bottom

07:08.052 --> 07:11.596
but welcome to academia.

07:11.598 --> 07:13.889
Once everyone gets
to know you, Elizabeth

07:13.891 --> 07:17.267
I think you'll find we have
a good bunch of folks here.

07:17.269 --> 07:18.810
Hearts are in the right place.

07:18.812 --> 07:20.521
It's fine.

07:20.523 --> 07:24.108
I'm used to it. Really.

07:24.110 --> 07:28.111
October 21st, 1805

07:28.113 --> 07:30.947
Napoleon's Navy,
under the command

07:30.949 --> 07:34.284
of Admiral
Pierre de Villenueve

07:34.286 --> 07:37.372
is wiped out
by the British Fleet

07:37.374 --> 07:42.543
under the command
of Admiral Horatio Nelson.

07:42.545 --> 07:47.005
This engagement, known as
the Battle of Trafalgar

07:47.007 --> 07:49.966
establishes Britain's dominance

07:49.968 --> 07:54.971
of the high seas
for the century to come.

07:54.973 --> 07:58.183
Surprisingly,
such a stinging defeat

07:58.185 --> 08:01.478
does little to deter Napoleon.

08:01.480 --> 08:04.065
If anything, his obsession

08:04.067 --> 08:06.067
with crossing the Channel

08:06.069 --> 08:08.860
only grows after Trafalgar.

08:08.862 --> 08:10.238
[KNOCKS ON DOOR]

08:10.240 --> 08:12.531
- Am I interrupting?
- Not at all.

08:12.533 --> 08:14.449
Couple of housekeeping matters.

08:14.451 --> 08:16.702
Would you prefer using your
own email for correspondence?

08:16.704 --> 08:18.329
Or I can set you up
with a department address?

08:18.331 --> 08:19.788
Neither.

08:19.790 --> 08:21.873
I'm old school that way.

08:21.875 --> 08:23.668
- Really?
- Really.

08:23.670 --> 08:26.421
- I prefer hard copies.
- Okay.

08:26.423 --> 08:28.171
Can I have your cell number
for the office?

08:28.173 --> 08:29.673
Don't have one.

08:29.675 --> 08:30.841
You don't have a cell phone?

08:30.843 --> 08:32.217
No, I don't.

08:32.220 --> 08:33.344
Home phone number.

08:33.346 --> 08:35.429
Sorry.

08:35.432 --> 08:39.224
Well, how do you communicate
with the world?

08:39.226 --> 08:40.184
Slowly.

08:45.692 --> 08:48.610
[INSTRUMENTAL MUSIC]

08:56.201 --> 08:59.121
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

09:32.864 --> 09:35.783
[BEEPING]

09:46.293 --> 09:48.920
It's all so close, isn't it?

09:48.922 --> 09:52.214
The pieces, the stars

09:52.216 --> 09:53.967
they are aligning.

09:57.054 --> 09:58.887
[SIGHS]

09:58.889 --> 10:01.223
What a view you have here.

10:01.225 --> 10:03.142
Majestic.

10:03.144 --> 10:06.436
The entire compound
is just breathtaking.

10:06.438 --> 10:10.858
Thank you. It's been
in my family for generations.

10:10.860 --> 10:12.445
I don't really like the lake.

10:13.904 --> 10:17.323
Too many bugs, water's too cold,
no sand.

10:17.325 --> 10:19.786
I know, right? Poor me.

10:25.000 --> 10:26.793
You're having doubts.

10:33.508 --> 10:35.468
[CREAKING]

10:39.806 --> 10:40.724
[GUN COCKING]

10:45.102 --> 10:47.021
[CREAKING]

10:51.985 --> 10:53.903
[WIND HUSTLING]

11:07.167 --> 11:08.084
[GUN CLICKING]

11:15.424 --> 11:17.343
[EXHALES]

11:45.663 --> 11:48.582
[KEYS CLACKING]

11:57.216 --> 12:01.886
By that definition, the US
military uses WMDs every day

12:01.888 --> 12:04.222
and theoretically could be
prosecuted by foreign governments

12:04.224 --> 12:06.848
if they were to adopt
a similar law.

12:06.850 --> 12:09.435
For example,
the N67 hand grenade

12:09.437 --> 12:14.523
is a fragmentation device with an
explosive charge of 6.5 ounces.

12:14.525 --> 12:18.402
So, it qualifies as a WMD
on two counts.

12:18.404 --> 12:19.403
Dannisha?

12:19.405 --> 12:20.405
When you say "Prosecuted

12:20.407 --> 12:22.656
by foreign governments"

12:22.658 --> 12:25.575
you mean prosecuted
as war criminals.

12:25.577 --> 12:29.497
That exact definition,
that wording

12:29.499 --> 12:32.085
I believe, is a matter
for the courts to decide.

12:40.759 --> 12:43.094
Does a figure this polarizing
earn the right

12:43.096 --> 12:46.180
to be given a platform like
this just for her notoriety?

12:46.182 --> 12:48.682
Some will say yes,
uh, some will say no.

12:48.684 --> 12:50.977
Some will say she shouldn't
even be walking free.

12:50.979 --> 12:53.478
But you have to look
to the GU administration

12:53.480 --> 12:55.732
for the real reason
behind this.

12:55.734 --> 12:56.733
Money.

12:56.735 --> 12:57.693
[DOOR OPENS]

12:58.945 --> 13:01.906
[MOANING]

13:03.783 --> 13:06.408
- Oh, fuck.
- What the fuck?

13:06.410 --> 13:07.910
Now, Martin, you show up now?

13:07.912 --> 13:09.704
Just leavin'.

13:09.706 --> 13:11.914
What, hold, we can go
in my room. You don't have to...

13:11.916 --> 13:13.752
No, I'm out of here. Thanks.

13:16.587 --> 13:18.463
[SIGHS]

13:18.465 --> 13:20.297
What was he doing
in the dark like that?

13:20.299 --> 13:22.300
This is what I've been saying.

13:22.302 --> 13:25.221
[TRAIN HORN BLARING]

13:35.523 --> 13:39.108
I am concerned much of
the analysis is unsubstantiated.

13:39.110 --> 13:40.984
Some will say
it's all circumstantial.

13:40.986 --> 13:43.237
But that's nonsense. Do you
think it's circumstantial?

13:43.239 --> 13:46.199
No, I do not. But wanting
to believe something...

13:46.201 --> 13:49.535
Do you realize that Pearl Harbor

13:49.537 --> 13:53.122
to V-J Day was less than
four years?

13:53.124 --> 13:55.791
A world at war,
and we ended it..

13:55.793 --> 13:56.792
[SNAPS FINGERS]

13:56.794 --> 13:58.710
...just that quickly?

13:58.712 --> 14:03.257
This thing has been going on
since the turn of the century.

14:03.259 --> 14:05.175
We have turned a side show
into the main event.

14:05.177 --> 14:08.595
But the response
has to be specific, surgical.

14:08.597 --> 14:12.307
I do think we need to take into account
the reactions, both at home and abroad.

14:12.309 --> 14:16.020
Doesn't it bother you
that the idea

14:16.022 --> 14:19.190
of American exceptionalism
is an anachronism?

14:19.192 --> 14:20.400
Of course.

14:20.402 --> 14:22.484
We're a rudderless ship

14:22.486 --> 14:24.903
where just getting by
is enough.

14:24.905 --> 14:28.366
And Los Angeles certainly showed
how tenuous even that is.

14:28.368 --> 14:30.701
If Maleki's tire
does not blow out

14:30.703 --> 14:32.994
if the CHP does not pull over

14:32.996 --> 14:35.873
if Maleki does not panic.

14:35.875 --> 14:38.542
If, if, if!

14:38.544 --> 14:41.295
An if prevented a catastrophe

14:41.297 --> 14:44.172
that would've made 9/11
look like a footnote.

14:44.174 --> 14:47.261
Now, I don't sleep well at night
knowing that.

14:48.971 --> 14:52.558
We have to win this war.
Total victory.

15:59.458 --> 16:02.378
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

16:14.974 --> 16:17.057
Thanks for coming
on such short notice.

16:17.059 --> 16:18.517
So you want
all of these changed?

16:18.519 --> 16:20.310
Plus the mudroom and back door.

16:20.312 --> 16:22.104
I wanna add
more locks there, too.

16:22.106 --> 16:23.980
A different key for each.

16:23.982 --> 16:24.900
Okay.

16:28.238 --> 16:29.737
You have a robbery?

16:29.739 --> 16:31.155
No.

16:31.157 --> 16:33.574
Not happy
with your alarm system?

16:33.576 --> 16:34.617
No, it's fine.

16:34.619 --> 16:35.618
If you want cameras,
I have a guy.

16:35.620 --> 16:36.870
No cameras.

16:37.913 --> 16:38.831
Thanks.

16:42.418 --> 16:43.836
I'll get to it.

16:47.756 --> 16:50.676
[WHIRRING]

17:20.039 --> 17:22.625
Sorry if I, uh, spooked you guys
last night.

17:23.835 --> 17:27.087
- Is he...
- No, Neal is gone.

17:38.849 --> 17:42.142
Hey, uh, if we want
this roommate thing to work out

17:42.144 --> 17:43.894
we need to communicate
a little bit better.

17:43.896 --> 17:45.938
- You know what I mean?
- Uh, yeah.

17:45.940 --> 17:47.856
So if you have a problem with
my bringing Neil back here...

17:47.858 --> 17:49.359
Uh, I don't, I don't have
a problem with that.

17:49.361 --> 17:51.902
- Okay, so what is your problem?
- I don't have a fucking..

17:51.904 --> 17:53.865
[SIREN WAILING AT DISTANCE]

17:55.366 --> 17:57.117
I don't have a fucking problem.

17:58.912 --> 18:01.578
Look, Martin, we don't really
know each other.

18:01.580 --> 18:04.498
I've got the sense you're one of those
extremely gifted, self-motivated types.

18:04.500 --> 18:08.920
Your test scores, the Ivy
League pedigree, the awards.

18:08.922 --> 18:12.006
Frankly a little intimidating,
but I applaud all that, seriously.

18:12.008 --> 18:14.257
It's just the sneaking around
that weirds me out a bit.

18:14.259 --> 18:17.886
Sneaking around?
What the fuck does that mean?

18:17.888 --> 18:20.681
You just seem really unhappy.

18:20.683 --> 18:21.766
Maybe you should
talk to someone.

18:21.768 --> 18:22.933
You know, if you want
a new roommate

18:22.935 --> 18:23.934
you just go ahead and say it.

18:23.936 --> 18:25.228
That's not what I'm saying.

18:25.230 --> 18:27.063
Well, fuck it.

18:27.065 --> 18:28.271
Opt room for a single
next semester.

18:28.273 --> 18:29.356
That's not what I'm saying.

18:29.358 --> 18:31.150
Hey, I get it, Jordan.

18:31.152 --> 18:32.778
It's what I'm saying.

18:38.617 --> 18:41.495
[BREATHING HEAVILY]

19:03.308 --> 19:06.270
[INDISTINCT CHATTER ON PA]

19:30.127 --> 19:33.337
And the paper..

19:33.339 --> 19:35.840
Is it good?

19:35.842 --> 19:39.509
Our circulation
continues to dwindle.

19:39.511 --> 19:42.346
Last time I checked,
uh, we had a grand total

19:42.348 --> 19:45.224
of 43,000 subscribers.

19:45.226 --> 19:47.392
The entire newsroom is comprised

19:47.394 --> 19:51.814
of an ever-dwindling 25,
myself included.

19:51.816 --> 19:54.776
Dwindling being key word here.

19:54.778 --> 19:56.195
Can I help you?

20:00.825 --> 20:04.160
At least they didn't
try to take a picture.

20:04.162 --> 20:06.371
So sorry, Mr. Lamm,
just a couple of minutes

20:06.373 --> 20:07.788
and your table will be ready.

20:07.790 --> 20:08.873
Thank you very much.

20:08.875 --> 20:11.836
[SIREN BLARING AT DISTANCE]

20:15.548 --> 20:17.882
You were saying about the paper?

20:17.884 --> 20:21.052
Oh, th... tha... that's it,
really.

20:21.054 --> 20:22.761
You know, sometimes I think
that leaving the Post

20:22.763 --> 20:25.305
was the biggest mistake
of my professional career.

20:25.307 --> 20:27.100
And then I remember

20:27.102 --> 20:28.892
I wasn't even given a choice
in the matter.

20:28.894 --> 20:32.563
Daddy, I am so sorry

20:32.565 --> 20:34.273
if I had anything to do
with you losing...

20:34.275 --> 20:36.817
That was not your fault.

20:36.819 --> 20:38.404
You know that.

20:39.698 --> 20:41.282
Even your mother has..

20:43.159 --> 20:44.909
Does she know how I feel?

20:44.911 --> 20:47.370
She read your letters, yes.

20:47.372 --> 20:48.830
And she still refuses to see me.

20:48.832 --> 20:52.083
We were so proud of you.

20:52.085 --> 20:53.750
So proud
of your accomplishments.

20:53.752 --> 20:54.670
Were.

20:56.839 --> 20:58.924
And now you're ashamed.

21:06.891 --> 21:09.811
[INDISTINCT CHATTER ON PA]

21:37.087 --> 21:40.841
We have to win this war.
Total victory.

21:42.969 --> 21:45.635
Now, more than anyone

21:45.637 --> 21:51.351
you... have done more
to prepare this country

21:51.353 --> 21:53.145
for this moment.

21:55.522 --> 21:59.107
So connect the dots
that need to be connected.

21:59.109 --> 22:03.365
And if the stars
need help aligning, do so.

22:04.740 --> 22:06.657
Talk to Adrian.

22:06.659 --> 22:08.953
The DI is with us on this.

22:15.167 --> 22:18.335
People wanna believe
what you say.

22:18.337 --> 22:20.962
Use that gift.

22:20.964 --> 22:25.426
And if you see this through
to its logical end

22:25.428 --> 22:29.389
your future, your legacy

22:29.391 --> 22:32.141
will be assured.

22:32.143 --> 22:35.730
You will have served
your country honorably.

22:46.865 --> 22:47.826
[DEVICE BEEPING]

22:59.546 --> 23:00.961
Do you see it?

23:00.963 --> 23:02.381
Uh, found it.

23:05.426 --> 23:07.719
[CHUCKLES]

23:07.721 --> 23:09.011
It's quite beautiful.

23:09.013 --> 23:10.388
Built in 1900

23:10.390 --> 23:13.474
by the legendary J.D. McCarthy
Safe and Lock Company

23:13.476 --> 23:14.558
out of Cincinnati.

23:14.560 --> 23:15.978
It's in excellent condition.

23:17.521 --> 23:19.106
The lock still works?

23:21.567 --> 23:25.652
You look awfully familiar.
Have we met?

23:25.654 --> 23:28.074
No, I'm afraid not.

23:28.991 --> 23:33.076
Of course. Excuse me.

23:33.078 --> 23:36.413
I just wanna say thank you
for your service to the country.

23:36.415 --> 23:39.334
You did what had to be done,
and we're safer for it.

23:39.336 --> 23:42.754
Well, thank you.

23:42.756 --> 23:45.256
I'm glad you feel safe.

23:45.258 --> 23:47.552
Well, let's open this bad boy.

23:53.892 --> 23:56.811
[INSTRUMENTAL MUSIC]

24:00.856 --> 24:02.774
Uh, a little help, please?

24:02.776 --> 24:06.777
Continuing our discussion
of Clausewitz and war

24:06.779 --> 24:09.279
in 1832, he wrote

24:09.281 --> 24:11.449
"Kind-hearted people
might, of course, think

24:11.451 --> 24:14.744
"there was some ingenious way
to disarm or defeat the enemy

24:14.746 --> 24:16.536
"without too much bloodshed.

24:16.538 --> 24:20.708
"It might imagine this as the
true goal of the art of war.

24:20.710 --> 24:22.919
"Pleasant as it sounds

24:22.921 --> 24:25.796
"it is a fallacy
that must be exposed.

24:25.798 --> 24:27.632
"War is such
a dangerous business

24:27.634 --> 24:29.508
"that mistakes
that come from kindness

24:29.510 --> 24:31.346
are the very worst."

24:51.031 --> 24:53.992
[CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKS]

25:14.931 --> 25:17.851
[CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKS]

25:28.153 --> 25:30.070
[CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKS]

25:43.167 --> 25:46.086
[INSTRUMENTAL MUSIC]

26:54.279 --> 26:57.241
[DEVICE BEEPING]

27:03.789 --> 27:05.709
[BEEPING RAPIDLY]

27:16.553 --> 27:17.470
[CREAKING]

28:00.055 --> 28:01.014
[FLOORBOARD CREAKING]

28:26.663 --> 28:27.581
[SNIFFS]

29:02.909 --> 29:05.829
[INSTRUMENTAL MUSIC]

30:43.634 --> 30:44.719
Hey, Libby.

30:47.346 --> 30:49.430
It's good to see you.

30:49.432 --> 30:50.349
Adrian.

30:54.354 --> 30:56.938
- How late?
- About three.

30:56.940 --> 30:58.857
Waiting for Amman to check in.

31:01.528 --> 31:03.654
I missed waking up to you
this morning.

31:06.324 --> 31:08.199
Me, too.

31:08.201 --> 31:09.825
I guess I've become
kind of used to it.

31:09.827 --> 31:10.826
[CHUCKLES]

31:10.828 --> 31:12.745
Me, too.

31:12.747 --> 31:15.748
The Amman call.
What you wanted to hear?

31:15.750 --> 31:16.833
No.

31:16.835 --> 31:19.209
What, the stars aren't aligning?

31:19.211 --> 31:21.504
Not funny.

31:21.506 --> 31:23.672
Did you tell Rachel?

31:23.674 --> 31:25.882
Nope.

31:25.884 --> 31:28.469
Are you waiting
for the right moment?

31:28.471 --> 31:30.388
I don't think
there is a right moment.

31:30.390 --> 31:31.349
[KNOCK ON DOOR]

31:32.933 --> 31:34.057
She would like to see you.

